<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I am not going to debate the effectiveness of getting exp though Quad kitting group or AoE groups, these are by far the mose efficent methods of geting exp in the game. <P>I am not even going to discuss the difficulty of getting and AoE group started or the dangers of Quadkitting without sow. If you can start these group or Quadkite safely, well the more power to you.<P>However did you know that quad kiting was never intended by EQ?<P>If you read the offical boards before they were shut down you may have read some of the posts from EQ reps on this subject. Basically the posts stated that quad kiting was an unforseen use of snar combined with AoE spells. <P>EQ gets many complaints about quad kiting and players dieing from Quad kiters trains when they loose controle and gate or zone leaving there mess behind.<P>If you look at the details of the quadkiting section of the class balance link on this site you will see a watered down version of what EQ was saying. The following is taken from the class ballance details :<P>Is this something that characters should be able to do? The two classes that seem to be able to do this are wizards and druids. Perhaps the tactic is hard and time consuming and should be left as is.<P>The original statment from EQ durring the class discussions was that Quad kiting was not intended and should not be alowed. After this statment many wizards posted there discontent with EQ's postition, saying that this was one of the only perks of the wizard class and taking it away would leave us with nothing. After a barash of posts EQ posted this more ambiguous statment, but it basically means the same thing. EQ is currently deciding weather or not wizard and druids will be alowd to contunue to quad kite.<P>Personaly I disaprove of quad kiting becuase it puts other players in danger when the quad kiter looses controle. However the only way to prevent quad kiting is to do one of two things.<P>1. ) Nerf Bonds of force ( either take it away compleatly and dont give us a snare spell untill a high lvl when we can no longer quad kite effectivly, or give it a much higher resist rate when we are solo or in a 2 man groups. )<P>2. ) Nerf AoE spells ( by either reducing there damage to the point we can not kill a mob worth exp with AoE's or install an effect that disrupts snar when an AoE is used. )<P>I am not particularly fond of either of these nerfs, as Bonds of force is also needed to solo single mobs, and AoEs are our only realy effective means of doing real damage ( even though I rarly get to use them myself, if I need an area effect spell I use a PB ).<P><BR>As for AoE groups:<P>I never saw anything on the EQ offical bords regarding there spacific positions on these tactics. However I have read posts from several wizards who were suspended for useing AoE tactics becuase they violate the Play Nice Police of EQ by disrupting zones and exploiting bad mob pathing. These guys may have done soemthing else to get suspended and were just blaming the tactics, but before you assume this read EQ Play Nice Policys.<P>This policy can be found on the EQ official site at :<BR> <A HREF="http://everquest.station.sony.com/support/policies/conduct.jsp" TARGET=_blank>http://everquest.station.sony.com/support/policies/conduct.jsp</A> <P>Rules<P>12<P>You will not exploit any bug in EverQuest and you will not communicate the existence of any such exploitable bug (bugs that grant the user unnatural or unintended benefits in game), either directly or through public posting, to any other user of EverQuest. You will promptly report any such bug via the in-game "/bug" command or via the eqtesting@verant.com email address.<P>( I am showing this rule because many AoE tactics exploit pathing bugs )<P><BR>Play Nice Rules 1.1 <P>6<P>You may not disrupt the normal playability of a zone or area. <BR>Zone/Area Disruption is defined as any activity designed to harm or inconvenience a number of groups rather than a specific player or group of players. This includes things such as:<P>„h Monopolizing most or all of the kills in an area. <BR>„h Deliberately blocking a doorway or narrow area so other players cannot get past. <BR>„h Refusing to cooperate with the other parties at a contested spawn site after having been instructed to do so by an EQCSR. <BR>„h Making excessive and inappropriate use of zone-wide communications (/shout, /ooc, /auction). <P>( The fist bullet is what shows EQ interprets AoE groups as being disruptive to zones, by monopolizing kills in a wide area )<P>7<P>You may not intentionally cause experience loss to another player, such as by "training" them. <BR>Training is defined as pulling an NPC along behind you and attempting to get it to attack another player who does not desire that engagement.<BR>The intentional training of NPCs will result in immediate disciplinary action when witnessed by an EQCSR. We are aware that accidents often happen causing unintentional trains, and will scrutinize each report of this activity closely.<P>( One train from an AoE group or a QuadKitting soloist may not be considered intentional but the more it is done the more trains that will be caused and the more likely it is to be considered intentional because you are aware of the danger you are putting other players in and you still choose to perform these actions )<P>I personaly dont have any problem with AoE groups, as they are just as dangerous to the AoE group ( if not more so ) as they are to any other players in the game. However I realy think that if these tactics become widely used there will be a magor nerf to AoE and PB spells.<P>Currently I dont think there are enought AoE groups out there that EQ would actually nerf spells for these type of tactics; they can just force AoE groups to disband or suspend AoE groups members if they are truly disrupting an area. However I assure you Quad kiting has already gotten there attention and there is probably some kind of nerf being planed for our emmidiate future.<P>If you dont want to see this happen I sugest you post to EQ and let them know your position on the subject before they take action.<P>Good luck    <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> <P>< this post was edited after a response from Wrathe ><P>( Please note I am not recomending that you state wether or not you aprove of quad kiting in any post you send to EQ. Recently it was pointed out to me that if a wizard or druid states that they do not aprove of quad kiting that EQ might use this as more resone to nerf this ability. I did not think about that at the time I sent my post and I have now send a retraction statment to EQ, but I dont want anyone to compound my error. )
</FONT>
